Toggle navigation En français Browse Job Listings FAQ Contact Register Log in Log in Forgot password? Intermediate Specialist, Data Support (RDM) Ottawa , ON Description Locations: Ottawa, ON, Morisset HallTime type : Full timeJob requisition id : JR7360Job Type: Employee Duration in Months (for fixed-term jobs): N/A Job Family: Library and Archives # of Open Positions: 1 Faculty/Service – Department: Research Data Management Services Campus: Morisset Hall Union Affiliation: SSUO Date Posted: December 21, 2023 Closing Date: January 22, 2024 Note: Applications will be accepted until 11:59 PM on the day prior to the Posting End Date aboveHours per week: 35 Salary Grade: SSUO Grade 10 Salary Range: $75,743.00 – $95,678.00 Position Title: Intermediate Specialist, Data Support (RDM)Position Number:103727Faculty / Service and Department: LibraryPosition Reports to: Research Data Management LibrarianJob Description Last Reviewed April 2023 Position PurposeThe Intermediate Specialist, Data Support (RDM) supports users through specialized consultation services that enable researchers to effectively manage, curate, publish, and preserve their primary source research data. The incumbent contributes to the goals of the University of Ottawa Research Data Management strategy to uphold principles and best practices in research data management such as TCPS2 and FAIR Data principles, which ensure high-quality and securely and ethically stored research data, and where possible, continued accessibility and reusability of this data.Specific Accountabilities1.Curation services: Takes a user-centred approach to assist researchers in the preparation and deposit of primary source research datasets into institutional data repository infrastructure. Tracks data curation workflow using appropriate tools.2. Research data quality assurance: Reviews and assesses researcher-prepared primary source data sets to identify potential threats to data security; and monitors compliance with institutional, national and international standards (eg. FAIR data) for deposit in institutionally supported data repository infrastructure (eg. Borealis (Dataverse). Notes data limitations and submits curation reports to the researcher with recommendations for data clean-up and resubmission.3. Research data management planning support: Identifies and recommends potential disciplinary-specific data repositories, or institutional data repository for data deposit. Provides expert consultation on best practices, national and disciplinary standards, and technical requirements for research data management, general and disciplinary-specific metadata description, and data documentation. Identifies and recommends potential software and tools for data re-use, management, security and curation.4. Workshops and training: As the lead contact or key support person for research data curation services, the incumbent provides direct one-on-one or group training to users, such as students, researchers, and research teams, in the adoption and adaptation of best practices and infrastructure, for the management of research data.5. Procedure development and awareness raising: Sets up consistent and ongoing procedures for research data deposit and curation and leads the development of tutorials, guides, documentation, and other self-learning tools to enable users to effectively access and fully utilize research data and related information resources for teaching, learning, and research activities.6. Infrastructure: Contributes to the ongoing design, development, maintenance, and improvement of infrastructure for research data curation services. Explores the use of applications and automated scripts to simplify workflows or solve problems.7.Data analysis and communication of results: Analyzes RDM services data downloaded through appropriated sources and identifies notable patterns and comparisons. Summarizes analysis, including using data visualization, in support of RDM service assessment and development.8. External liaison: Actively participates in national data infrastructure administrators’ group (eg. Scholars Portal Dataverse community meetings).9. Teamwork: Serves as a resource person for colleagues in the Research Services division, as well as across the Library, to provide research data management services. As a member of the Interdisciplinary Data Team (IDT), the Intermediate Specialist, Data Support (RDM) contributes to improvements to collections, services, and policy and procedures with a view to continuously adapting services to meet changing user needs. May be called upon to participate in the library’s online chat service, provide reference services of a general and a specialized nature to users of data resources in all supported formats, including related software and tools. May be called upon to provide back-up support for other members of the Interdisciplinary Data Team, as appropriate.10. Supervision: Supervises work performed by students and casual employees to organize priorities and provide guidance in the attainment of individual objectives.Knowledge, Experience and SkillsEssential QualificationsGraduate degree in data science, science, social sciences, or in a research data-intensive discipline, or equivalent professional experience.Minimum of four years’ experience with data collection, data analysis, or research data management, including techniques such as deidentification and anonymization, preferably in an academic or research-intensive setting. Key Competencies (required for all positions-cannot be modified)PlanningInitiativeClient service orientationTeamwork and cooperation Other QualificationsKnowledge of and experience with different qualitative and quantitative data types and formats including numeric, geospatial, image, and video, etcKnowledge of Indigenous data sovereignty and the application of equity, diversity and inclusion principles in the management of research data is an asset.Demonstrated experience with or understanding of scripting languages and/or tools for data manipulation (such as R, Python, CSS, HTML, Excel, OpenRefine)Demonstrated ability to exercise judgement when verifying the quality of data, and use computer systems and software for the manipulation and clean-up of data.Ability to communicate effectively with researchers from a variety of disciplines and backgroundsDemonstrated ability to work independently, manage multiple projects at once, to set priorities, meet deadlines, and work in teamsFamiliarity with database or repository structure and developmentFamiliarity with metadata standards to describe both data sets and variablesDemonstrated ability to identify and vet resources and tools for data sharing, analysis, and preservation.Attention to detailAbility to problem-solve through independent learningAbility to make public presentations in both official languagesBilingualism – French and English (spoken and written) Typical Contacts or Working RelationshipsLibrary users (students, professors, researchers, general public): DailyProvides reference services, of a general and a specialized nature, to users of data resources in all supported formats, including related software and tools.Library employees: DailyWorks closely with all members of the Research Division to respond to user inquiries and actively contributes to the development of new services offerings.May be called upon to provide back-up support for other members of the Interdisciplinary Data Team, as appropriate. Information Technology:WeeklyAddresses user concerns, such as those related to data software infrastructure (eg. secure drives, cloud storage, etc.).Other libraries, archives, museums, and external service providers (such as Scholars Portal):MonthlyInquires about services for users or to share information concerning best practices, including collaboration on special projects. Initiative, Problem Solving, Key Issues and ChallengesKey challenges may include: data security concerns, inconsistencies and limitations; in the course of analyzing and comparing multiple data sets the Intermediate Specialist, Data Support (RDM) will regularly identify, note, and address a course of action for resolving these issues.In order to determine the support need and level of service required by users, the Intermediate Specialist, Data Support (RDM) evaluate requests and prompt additional information. This requires the incumbent to formulate appropriate questions, interpret responses to determine complexity of a request, adapt the approach based on user type, and refer appropriately as needed.The Intermediate Specialist, Data Support (RDM) provides support for a wide range of complex and evolving tools, resources, and services including, but not limited to the deposition of datasets into data repositories. The Intermediate Specialist, Data Support (RDM)’s scope of expertise is broad and continually changing.The Research Intermediate Specialist, Data Support (RDM) will demonstrate initiative in establishing workflows related to data curation tracking and analysis processes.Working in a highly collaborative environment, the Research Data Management Analyst employs tact and effective interpersonal skills to maintain sustained working relationships with colleagues and users, and accomplish the work of assigned areas.To keep abreast of the evolving field of research data management and data-intensive scholarship, the Intermediate Specialist, Data Support (RDM)’s must continuously update their professional knowledge-base of software, tools, technologies, and techniques related to managing, curating, publishing, and preserving research data.In order to ensure that Library-produced learning tools remain up to date and relevant, the Intermediate Specialist, Data Support (RDM) must continually monitor and evaluate best practices in RDM and changes to the functionality and user interfaces of key data, GIS, and other Library resources, software, and tools. Decision MakingDecisions:Deploys their deep knowledge of existing collections, finding tools, and user needs to contribute to the ongoing, team-based work of promoting the use of software and tools to facilitate access to, and the use of, various data types.Responsible for determining the appropriate level of support in the use of data, data analysis software, related tools and general Library resources. Responsible for referring complex user requests to employees within the division and throughout the Library.Responsible for ensuring services they provide are aligned with internal and external efforts to improve information discovery, access, and preservation. Takes initiative to make recommendations on these practices. Beyond the tasks, objectives, and priorities identified in consultation with the incumbent’s supervisor, as well as providing point-in-time services to users, the incumbent exercises considerable autonomy in managing their workload, identifying opportunities for service development, and reporting on progress and challenges to their supervisor at regular intervals. Recommendations:With a deep understanding of data resources and user needs, the incumbent contributes to decision-making regarding infrastructure that could optimize data publishing, archiving and the ability of users to fully leverage these resources. They must be able to effectively communicate their recommendations, including the risks and benefits, to colleagues, superiors, and other stakeholders within the Library.Collaborates with colleagues in the division to make recommendations on technologies required to leverage data collections, based on a deep understanding of users’ data needs and a thorough understanding of the Library’s research data management services. Dimensions1,300 researchers supported by data curation at University of Ottawa1,242 data files from over 159 data sets in the uOttawa instance of Borealis (Dataverse)228,762 data files deposited from over 12,855 datasets across 1,077 collections covering multiple disciplines in Scholars Portal Borealis (Dataverse) Working Environment and ConditionsPhysical Effort:The incumbent is seated for most of the time. They will occasionally accompany users to various locations throughout the Library to assist with workstations or to locate items in the collection or other services within the Library. When offering presentations, they will be required to stand for short periods. They may occasionally be required to carry physical Library materials, not exceeding a few pounds.Physical Environment:The incumbent works in their office equipped with standard office furnishings and a workstation with dual monitors. They may occasionally work from other classrooms or meeting rooms on campus, both large and small.Sensory Attention:As the incumbent’s workstation is situated near Library users and other employees, they will be exposed to ambient levels of noise typically found in a quiet study area. The incumbent will be expected to listen attentively when exchanging with Library users, colleagues, and at meetings.Mental Stress:This position requires the incumbent to manage their priorities and own time effectively. Occasionally, this will cause stress as user demands are greater and more numerous during certain periods of the academic year. Deadlines must be met with respect to users’ academic needs. The ability to concentrate on precise tasks while occasionally being interrupted may also cause stress and requires the incumbent to develop good concentration skills in order to focus on work without being distracted.Occasionally, the incumbent will be required to modify their work hours to ensure service is provided during specific opening hours or to meet exceptional service requirements. This may require, for example, adjusting the workday in order to offer a workshop for an evening course.Key Competencies at uOttawa:Here are the required competencies for all or our employees at uOttawa: Planning: Organize in time a series of actions or events in order to realize an objective or a project. Plan and organize own work and priorities in regular daily activities.Initiative: Demonstrate creativity and initiative to suggest improvements and encourage positive results. Is proactive and self-starting. Show availability and willingness to go above and beyond whenever it is possible.Client Service Orientation: Help or serve others to meet their needs. This implies anticipating and identifying the needs of internal and external clients and finding solutions on how to meet them.Teamwork and Cooperation: Cooperate and work well with other members of the team to reach common goal(s). Accept and give constructive feedback. Able to adjust own behaviour to reach the goals of the team.The University of Ottawa embraces diversity and inclusion in the workplace. We are passionate about our people and committed to employment equity. We foster a culture of respect, teamwork and inclusion, where collaboration, innovation, and creativity fuel our quest for research and teaching excellence. While all qualified persons are invited to apply, we welcome applications from qualified Indigenous persons, racialized persons, persons with disabilities, women and LGBTQIA2S+ persons. The University is committed to creating and maintaining an accessible, barrier-free work environment. The University is also committed to working with applicants with disabilities requesting accommodation during the recruitment, assessment and selection processes. Applicants with disabilities may contact hrtalentmanagement@uottawa.ca to communicate the accommodation need. All qualified candidates are encouraged to apply; however, Canadians and permanent residents will be given priority.Note: if this is a union position: The hiring process will be governed by the current collective agreement related to the union affiliation noted above; you can click here to find out more.If this is a front-line position with responsibilities to interact with students, selected candidates must be rated at the Low Advanced proficiency level or higher for both oral comprehension and reading comprehension in their second official language. The rating is determined by a proficiency test designed by the Official Languages and Bilingualism Institute.Prior to May 1, 2022, the University required all students, faculty, staff, and visitors (including contractors) to be fully vaccinated against Covid-19 as defined in Policy 129 – Covid-19 Vaccination. This policy was suspended effective May 1, 2022 but may be reinstated at any point in the future depending on public health guidelines and the recommendations of experts.Applications should be submitted electronically through the University of Ottawa Careers website at the following link:https://uottawa.wd3.myworkdayjobs.com/en-US/uOttaw... Compensation $75,743.00 - $95,678.00 Closes: 21 January, 2024 University of Ottawa Library Ottawa , ON Policies and Terms of Use · jobboard@bcla.bc.ca / BCLA PO BOX 19008, Rocky Point PO, Port Moody, BC V3H 0J1 window.dataLayer = window.dataLayer || [];
